def clean_lyrics(lyrics):
    lyrics = re.sub(r'\[.*]', ' ', lyrics) #take out [verse 1], [chorus], [intro], [outro] etc 
    lyrics = re.sub(r'\n', ' ', lyrics) #remove new lines
    lyrics = re.sub('['+string.punctuation+']', '', lyrics) #remove all punc
    lyrics = filter(None, lyrics.split(' ')) #remove empty strings
    lyrics = ' '.join(lyrics)
    return lyrics.lower()
In [165]:
def clean_artist_name(name):
    name = name.replace(u'\u200b', '') #random thing attached to some artist names
    name = re.sub(r'\(.*\)', '', name)#remove parenthesis from like Kendrick Lamar (with SZA)
    return name.lower().strip()

The following function will return to us the lyrics of a song in the same form as presented on the Genius website, separated by intro, verse, chorus, etc.

In [171]:
def get_lyrics(song, artist):

    base_url = "http://api.genius.com"
    headers = {'Authorization': bearer_token}

    song_title = song
    artist_name = artist
    def get_api_path():
        if __name__ == "__main__":
            search_url = base_url + "/search"
            data = {'q': song_title}
            response = requests.get(search_url, params=data, headers=headers)
            json = response.json()
            song_info = None
        for hit in json["response"]["hits"]:
#         print(hit)
#             if clean_artist_name(hit["result"]["primary_artist"]["name"]) == clean_artist_name(artist_name):
            if clean_artist_name(artist_name) in clean_artist_name(hit["result"]["primary_artist"]["name"]):
                song_info = hit
                break
        if song_info:
            song_api_path = song_info["result"]["api_path"]
            return song_api_path
    def lyrics_from_song_api_path(song_api_path):
        if song_api_path == None:
            return np.nan
        song_url = base_url + song_api_path
        response = requests.get(song_url, headers=headers)
        json = response.json()
        path = json["response"]["song"]["path"]
        #gotta go regular html scraping... come on Genius
        page_url = "http://genius.com" + path
        page = requests.get(page_url)
        html = BeautifulSoup(page.text, "html.parser")
        
        [h.extract() for h in html('script')]

        lyrics = html.find('div', class_='lyrics').get_text() #updated css where the lyrics are based in HTML
        return lyrics
    return lyrics_from_song_api_path(get_api_path())

In [132]:
def get_sentiment(lyrics):
    docs = {'documents': [{'id': 0, 'language': 'en', 'text': lyrics}]}
    headers= {"Ocp-Apim-Subscription-Key": key}
    response  = requests.post(sentiment_api_url, headers=headers, json=docs)
    sentiments = response.json()
    return sentiments

def convert_durationms(time):
    seconds=(time/1000)%60
    minutes=(time/(1000*60))%60
    hours=(time/(1000*60*60))%24
    
    return minutes

Conclusion¶

To make a popular song, make the duration 3.7 minutes, 121 BPM, -5.4 DB, in key C#, somewhat positive, very energetic, repetitive (30% of words unique) and something people want to dance to.¶

def sort_second(val):
    return val[1]
def top_n_words_and_counts(lyrics, n):
    result = []
    for word in get_unique_words(lyrics):
        result.append([word,count_occurences(word, lyrics)])
    result.sort(key=sort_second, reverse=True)
    return result[:n]
def top_n_words(lyrics, n):
    result = []
    words = []
    for word in get_unique_words(lyrics):
        result.append([word,count_occurences(word, lyrics)])
    result.sort(key=sort_second, reverse=True)
    for i in range(n):
        words.append(result[i][0])
    return words
